=漢文 in Japan (Kanbun) and in Korea (Hanmun)= 

==Monographs== 
* Astrid Brochlos: Kanbun. Grundlagen der klassischen sino-japanischen Schriftsprache. Wiesbaden: Harrassowitz, 2004.
* Sydney Crawcour: An introduction to Kanbun. Ann Arbor: University of Michigan, 1965
* Inge-Lore Kluge: Kanbun - ein Lehr- und Übungsbuch. Frankfurt am Main: Lang, 1997.
* Komai Kanbun Textbook [[@http://n-iyanaga.la.coocan.jp/school_manuals/Komai_Kanbun_textbook-JPN-OCR.pdf|pdf]] 

==Articles== 
* Judith N. Rabinovitch: An introduction to Hentai Kambun [Variant Chinese], a hybrid Sinico-Japanese used by the male elite in premodern Japan. Journal of Chinese Linguistics. Vol. 24, No. 1 (1996).
* Romuald Huszcza: Antonymous Hanmun pairs in Korean and other East Asian languages. Journal of Chinese Linguistics. Vol. 15, No. 1 (1987).
* Edith Aldridge: Hentai Kambun Perspective on Short Scrambling. Journal of East Asian Linguistics Vol. 10, No. 2 (Apr., 2001), pp. 169-200 [[@http://Stable%20URL:%20http://www.jstor.org/stable/20100798|JSTOR]]
* Murai Shosuke: Poetry in Chinese as a Diplomatic Art in Premodern East Asia. In: Andrew Edmund Goble [Hrsg.]: Tools of culture. Ann Arbor, Michigan: Association for Asian Studies, 2009: 49-70
* Robert Borgen: "The Politics of Classical Chinese in the Early Japanese Court." Rhetoric and the Discourses of Power in Court Culture China, Europe, and Japan. Ed. by D. R. Knechtges and E. Vance. Washington: University of Washington Press, 2005: 199-238.


